Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

IIUC this would break existing deployments, so this patch is non-backportable to me.

Patch Set 1:

@frickler, Yes, it would break existing py3 deployments so probably not nice for a stable release, but it would fix py2 deployments that upgrade to py3. Definitely a trade off and I'm not sure it's worth it either.

Patch Set 1:

One solution this is a bit more involved would be to introduce a flag to switch this behaviour that is immediately deprated again.

That way operators could change the setup on their own pace, instead of being broken by a simple minor update.

But I'm also not sure whether just sticking to the status quo for the stable branches would be better. You can still carry the patch downstream in Ubuntu, as I think you are already doing anyway IIRC.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I think that backporting this DB migration to a stable branch is not advisable since it may fail when the existing data don't match the constraints.

Patch Set 1:

> I think that backporting this DB migration to a stable branch is
 > not advisable since it may fail when the existing data don't match
 > the constraints.

I kinda agree, but not sure what is worse. If you hit this bug, it's dangerous to run Designate, as it will create an infinite (only limited by disk/memory) number of service records. Not sure which is better.

Patch Set 1:

As has been stated, without this patch you can run into the problem of designate killing your database by flooding the service_statuses table. Upgrading to this patch only takes effect if the migration is executed and that will expectedly fail if you are hitting the bug. But isn't that actually useful? i.e. it serves as a red flag that you have a serious problem that needs resolving and the solution is documented in the LP bug. So personally I am favour of having this backported because whatever the outcome i believe it is advantageous to have this patch.
Abandoned

Patch Set 3:

I'm wondering if we need microversions to do an API change like this.

Otherwise, how can a consumer know whether they are talking to an API that allows setting serials? Not sure if telling them "Just try it and see whether it works" is a valid answer.

Patch Set 3: Workflow-1

So, in Designate, we (traditionally - when the team make up was very different) have held a differing view on API compatiblity to other projects, namely that we will non backwards breaking changes.

My view would be that with microversions, we would give the user the same experience - that a system with an older version would fail to work.

I am open to debate on this though.

I did have a thought that we could make this a "task" on the zone, as we will probably need one at some point in the future to trigger a serial rollover anyway.

WIP'ing until we decide whats right to do

Patch Set 3:

JFYI: tested this patch shortly. Turned out that when increment_serial is not True, the SOA record of the zone won't get updated.
 See: https://github.com/openstack/designate/blob/master/designate/central/service.py#L495-L510 - the _update_soa() won't be called when increment_serial is empty.
Abandoned

Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Thanks Dimitry!

Unfortunately we do not allow users to specify an exact pool ID - we use a scheduler to find the right zone [1]

I suggest we implement a `Designate-Zone-Attributes` header. (We drop the "X-" prefix these days)[2]

It should take a comma separated key:value list like this:

  Designate-Zone-Attributes:  pool_level: gold, fast_ttl: true, pops: global

and then pass them as attributes on the zone being created to central

1 - https://docs.openstack.org/designate/latest/admin/pool-scheduler.html
2- http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/api-wg/guidelines/headers.html

Patch Set 2:

Hi Graham,

Please correct me if I'm wrong, but there is a 'pool_id_attribute_filter' (https://docs.openstack.org/designate/latest/admin/pool-scheduler.html#pool-id-attribute-filter)

Which we use successfully and which allows to specify 'pool_id' in attributes during zone creation. But unfortunately not during the zone import because the request has 'text/dns' content type. 

Obviously, this implementation assumes that 'pool_id_attribute_filter' is enabled.

Also, according to my understanding of RFC2616: 
https://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec4.html#sec4.2
 the header field-value may have multiple comma-separated values, but not multiple key-value pairs like:
pool_level: gold, fast_ttl: true, pops: global

Patch Set 2:

OK, this slipped off my radar.

I am not comfortable with allowing Pool-ID to be the only schedualer - I do not think it is a pattern we should allow.

Can we look at multipart mime types?

Adding a JSON section with attributes then the text/dns section would allow us to have the same experience for import as we have for create

Patch Set 2:

OK, another problem that I've encountered is: https://bugs.launchpad.net/designate/+bug/1749669

Right now using 'attribute' and 'pool_id_attribute' filters will not allow schedule by pool_id at all.

I understand your idea, but this won't work until the problem mentioned above is resolved.
Abandoned

Patch Set 7:

Do we really require nginx here?

Patch Set 7:

We likely need something more than certbot since the ACME response web server needs to bind to non standard (not 80 or 443) port and the local ip address (not that domain ip address). Certbot standalone does not seem to be very configurable.

Patch Set 7:

Hmm... but then why not the already installed apache?

Patch Set 7:

> Hmm... but then why not the already installed apache?

There is no technical reason why nginx must be used. I wasn't aware that Apache is installed by default everywhere, and noticed bifrost was using nginx. I know that all the wsgi processes use apache but wasn't aware it was used for anything else. I'm not tied to nginx; it's the first tool I reached for. Probably rewriting the acme server config wouldn't be too hard.

As James says, the reason for the server at all is that certbot is not enough. In fact, when you run certbot in standalone mode, it will temporarily bind a HTTP server on to 80 to do the ACME HTTP challenge. The spec does not allow binding on to higher ports, as this opens it up to spurious authenticity claims. Because HAProxy is already going to be listening on that port, there is additional work in Kolla-Ansible to send requests on to the ACME server instead of Horizon if the request is for the well-known ACME challenge path.
